[conversation_rho]
{
	[text*]
	{
		choice = shop;
		screen_text = "Having the well filled means we aren't going to die of thirst, but with the forges of the Fire King blasting night and day, it won't be long before the Krug come calling in numbers we can't hope to stand against.\n\nUnless you've got it in you to march up Mount Underforge and talk some sense into the Fire King, you may as well head back to wherever you came from and let us die in peace.";
	  f scroll_rate = 6.500000;
	}
}
[conversation_scribe]
{
	[text*]
	{
		order = 0;
		choice = more;
		screen_text = "Our Undertaker came clean with us, friend. We are indeed in a bad place. If it weren't for you, we might have frozen in the snows only to have our bones baked in these sands. We seem to have made it, and so have you, so there is still hope.\n\nThe Undertaker let me take a look at an acolyte's journal mentioning this Chalice of Mourning you seek; would you like to hear what I have found?";
	  f scroll_rate = 6.500000;
	}
	[text*]
	{
		order = 1;
		choice = more;
		screen_text = "It appears that the Chalice of Mourning was used during the ritual preparation of the Valley of the Dead. Anything placed within the Chalice and allowed to rest in the midday sun would be granted temporary binding to the Valley.\n\nThis was apparently used on just about everything there, including the inks of the protective runes, the ashes of his servants, and the perfumes to douse the chambers, but here's where it gets interesting...";
	  f scroll_rate = 6.500000;
	}
	[text*]
	{
		order = 2;
		choice = more;
		screen_text = "Once the glyphs had been set, the living could only enter the Valley by drinking water prepared in the Chalice. The Fire King must have figured all this out, and used the Chalice to grant passage to his armies to attack the Snow Queen.\n\nWhat the journal doesn't mention, and what I think the Fire King hasn't figured out, is that removing the Chalice from the Valley has somehow broken the enchantments, and allowed the dead to roam free of the Valley.";
	  f scroll_rate = 6.500000;
	}
	[text*]
	{
		choice = shop;
		screen_text = "If the Fire King is still using it to enchant his armies, he must be bringing it to the surface to prepare the waters when the sun is high. I don't know if that helps you or not, but I found it interesting to say the least.\n\nI shouldn't keep you any more. If Yesterhaven is to survive to be more than a footnote in someone else's tome, you had better get moving. Our prayers are with you always, friend.";
	  f scroll_rate = 6.500000;
	}
}
[conversation_mayor]
{
	[text*]
	{
		screen_text = "You've saved us twice now, friend. I don't think there is anything we can do to repay that, but it looks like after all your hard work and bravery, we've only managed to tip the delicate balance of our land, and played into the hands of the Fire King.\n\nThe Snow Queen has realized the errors of her ways, but without your help, we have no hope of holding Yesterhaven against the armies of Underforge. Are you willing to fight for us once more, stranger? Perhaps the Fire King can be brought to his senses at the edge of your sword, much as the Snow Queen was.";
	  f scroll_rate = 6.500000;
	  activate_quest* = quest_fire;
		quest_dialog = true;
	}
}
